From: fyl@fylz.com (Phil Hughes)
Subject: Re: Zero Unix Expo Interest!
Date: Tue, 28 Sep 1993 16:09:24 GMT

Rasmus Lerdorf (rlerdorf@netcom.com) wrote:
: Someone in this group mentioned that one way of getting commercial
: developers interested in Linux would be to ask these vendours at
: Unix Expo for Linux versions of their products.  
: 
: Well, I represented a commercial vendour at Unix Expo, and from the
: look of recent discussion, a rather interesting one for Linux people.
: I was at the Cyclades booth.  Cyclades is an intelligent I/O card
: manufacturer.  I also represented Nutec Corp. which is a Unix
: software company.  I didn't have a single person stop by the booth
: interested in Linux.  Just about every other imaginable Intel-based
: Unix was mentioned, including BSD several times.  In fact, BSD had
: a booth very close to me.

I'm not that surprised.  First, because Linux users generally wouldn't
be going to Unix Expo and second because most Linux users just don't
expect that sort of support to be available -- yet.

Connecting commercial vendors with the Linux community is going to
take some work.  For example, I have spoken at the local (Seattle)
Unix Group meeting on Linux.  An overflow crowd (about 75) with a
followup meeting for questions and answers attended by around 30 --
all of whom are either running Linux or plan to run it.

I am also attempting to get a magazine, Linux Journal going.  (For
those who heard about it before it almost died but it looks like I
will be teaming up with a publisher of another UNIX-related
publication and it is going to happen.)  Much like small local
newspapers and small town local radio stations, the audience will have
a specific interest.  Advertising in such media can be a service to
the reader rather than just a way to pay for the publication.

Linux is very young.  It reminds me of the UNIX community of over 10
years ago.  Users are hungry for information and products but they
don't really know where to look.  I feel that marketing effort today
will pay off big in the long run.
-- 
